00:42:54.695 --> 00:42:56.855
So, or how far can it go?

00:42:56.855 --> 00:42:59.576
So say, you saw this happen with like chat GPT

00:42:59.576 --> 00:43:00.375
when it first came out,

00:43:00.935 --> 00:43:03.736
where people would ask it these sort of dumb questions

00:43:03.736 --> 00:43:09.736
of like, rewrite this email in the style of whatever,

00:43:09.736 --> 00:43:11.655
you know, like, and it had this sort of like,

00:43:11.655 --> 00:43:13.415
this was like this fun little gimmick that it can do.

00:43:14.776 --> 00:43:17.736
And at some point it was like, okay,

00:43:17.736 --> 00:43:18.535
I know what it's going to do.

00:43:18.535 --> 00:43:19.415
It's going to produce the thing.

00:43:19.415 --> 00:43:21.896
It's not, the artifact isn't that fun.

00:43:22.616 --> 00:43:24.776
It was sort of like the process of doing it that was fun

00:43:24.776 --> 00:43:25.736
and the artifact itself.

00:43:25.736 --> 00:43:26.776
I'm like, whatever.

00:43:26.776 --> 00:43:27.975
And to your point, if you have all these things,

00:43:27.975 --> 00:43:29.415
like churning away in your backlog,

00:43:29.415 --> 00:43:33.016
your project backlog, your idea backlog, basically.

00:43:33.016 --> 00:43:34.456
It'll be cleared out eventually.

00:43:34.456 --> 00:43:36.535
But it's partly that, but it's also like,

00:43:36.535 --> 00:43:40.456
if you just said, let me give you a two paragraph spec

00:43:40.456 --> 00:43:41.255
of the thing I want.

00:43:41.255 --> 00:43:42.616
You push one button and it's done.

00:43:43.576 --> 00:43:44.616
Do you think that's fun?

00:43:45.336 --> 00:43:49.336
Like, is it fun if it can really do the whole thing

00:43:49.415 --> 00:43:52.456
autonomously where like RoboRev was done in one,

00:43:52.456 --> 00:43:54.375
and if you can one shot RoboRev,

00:43:54.375 --> 00:43:55.415
would you have fun building it?

00:43:56.616 --> 00:43:57.576
I don't think so.

00:43:57.576 --> 00:43:58.216
Yeah.

00:43:58.216 --> 00:44:00.616
I think that, I think that the part of the fun,

00:44:00.616 --> 00:44:02.375
like part of the fun is the process

00:44:02.375 --> 00:44:04.616
and like seeing the, like seeing the thing,

00:44:04.616 --> 00:44:06.616
seeing the thing take shape, you know,

00:44:06.616 --> 00:44:08.616
kind of that feeling of like, you know,

00:44:08.616 --> 00:44:09.896
I'm not an artist, but you know,

00:44:09.896 --> 00:44:12.616
I imagine like what it might've seemed like to,

00:44:12.616 --> 00:44:15.336
you know, Leonardo da Vinci to like be chiseling,

00:44:15.336 --> 00:44:17.815
you know, chiseling David, like out of the block of,

00:44:17.815 --> 00:44:18.935
out of the block of marble.

00:44:18.935 --> 00:44:22.296
And, and a little bit like the, the agentic,

00:44:22.296 --> 00:44:25.016
agentic coding right now, you know,

00:44:25.016 --> 00:44:27.016
maybe that's a little bit of a grandiose analogy,

00:44:27.016 --> 00:44:29.736
but, but it does, it does feel like that a little bit

00:44:29.736 --> 00:44:32.456
where you can, you know, your feedback,

00:44:32.456 --> 00:44:34.296
like the feedback that I'm giving the agent,

00:44:34.296 --> 00:44:35.815
I can see the project,

00:44:35.815 --> 00:44:37.415
I can see the project taking shape.

00:44:37.415 --> 00:44:39.336
Like, you know, you, you can see that it's like,

00:44:40.375 --> 00:44:43.415
you know, it's the agent, agent's behavior out of the box.

00:44:43.415 --> 00:44:45.255
It gets most things wrong.

00:44:45.255 --> 00:44:46.935
And so you have to go through and like, you know,

00:44:46.935 --> 00:44:48.216
find all the things that I got wrong

00:44:48.216 --> 00:44:49.815
and get them and get them right.

00:44:49.815 --> 00:44:51.496
And then refine and refine and refine.

00:44:51.496 --> 00:44:53.095
And so it takes, you know,

00:44:53.095 --> 00:44:55.496
hundreds or thousands of iterations with the agent,

00:44:55.496 --> 00:44:57.655
you know, to make a thing that, that, you know,

00:44:57.655 --> 00:44:59.736
essentially meets, you know, meets my standards,

00:44:59.736 --> 00:45:00.375
which, you know, and I,

00:45:00.375 --> 00:45:02.056
and I have high standards for, for tools.

00:45:02.056 --> 00:45:03.655
And so, you know, maybe for other people

00:45:03.655 --> 00:45:04.535
it'd be different and like,

00:45:04.535 --> 00:45:06.616
maybe their one-shot, their one-shot tool,

00:45:07.736 --> 00:45:09.095
you know, would be, their,

00:45:09.095 --> 00:45:11.736
their one-shot tool would be like totally fine for them.

00:45:11.736 --> 00:45:13.496
You know, if it's like a piece of throwaway code,

00:45:13.496 --> 00:45:15.095
like it serves a one-time,

00:45:15.095 --> 00:45:17.016
a one-time use or like limited time use.

00:45:17.016 --> 00:45:19.896
But if it's a tool that you're going to be using for years,

00:45:19.896 --> 00:45:22.456
like I, the way I'm approaching it is like,

00:45:22.456 --> 00:45:24.135
I'm building things that I want to be using

00:45:24.135 --> 00:45:25.095
five years from now.

00:45:25.095 --> 00:45:26.535
And so I might as well, you know,

00:45:26.535 --> 00:45:28.456
put in the effort to do it the, you know,

00:45:29.255 --> 00:45:31.896
do it the right way and to make it, make it good.

00:45:31.896 --> 00:45:33.975
You know, but I don't know, it's fun.

00:45:33.975 --> 00:45:36.135
Like, I think the feeling won't last forever.

00:45:36.135 --> 00:45:38.935
And maybe a year from now, six months from now,

00:45:39.896 --> 00:45:41.576
it'll just feel like work again.

00:45:41.576 --> 00:45:44.375
And, you know, at six o'clock or seven o'clock,

00:45:44.375 --> 00:45:46.456
I'll be happy to close the laptop and say,

00:45:46.456 --> 00:45:47.655
you know, the day is done.

00:45:47.655 --> 00:45:48.375
Enough is enough.

00:45:48.375 --> 00:45:49.975
You know, it will, the agents will be there

00:45:49.975 --> 00:45:50.616
tomorrow morning.

00:45:50.616 --> 00:45:51.415
Yeah.

00:45:51.415 --> 00:45:55.016
It's, it's such an interesting point to like,

00:45:55.016 --> 00:45:57.176
the question of like, do you like closing your laptop?

00:45:57.176 --> 00:45:58.296
Like, are you having fun?

00:45:59.255 --> 00:46:01.016
Would you have fun if you could like

00:46:01.016 --> 00:46:02.375
snap it into existence?

00:46:02.935 --> 00:46:05.735
It feels like questions of like,

00:46:06.456 --> 00:46:07.815
what do engineers enjoy?

00:46:08.695 --> 00:46:11.495
What is like a person who might contract an engineer

00:46:11.495 --> 00:46:13.255
to like build something they want,

00:46:13.896 --> 00:46:14.396
enjoy?

00:46:14.935 --> 00:46:17.896
Like, who enjoys kind of like being in the process

00:46:17.896 --> 00:46:21.175
and maybe seeing the process sped up or automated?

00:46:21.815 --> 00:46:24.216
And who kind of just wants it done?

00:46:24.935 --> 00:46:27.576
Like, I guess like tools like RoboRev

00:46:27.576 --> 00:46:29.016
that you're talking about, that's very like.

00:46:29.016 --> 00:46:30.695
I guess I should explain what that is.

00:46:30.695 --> 00:46:31.016
Yeah.

00:46:31.016 --> 00:46:33.815
Or like a tool for reviewing commits,

00:46:33.815 --> 00:46:35.656
like RoboRev that kind of augments

00:46:35.656 --> 00:46:38.135
like the development process with AI.

00:46:38.135 --> 00:46:41.576
It's funny because it is kind of like an engineer's tool.

00:46:41.576 --> 00:46:43.096
Like it's something they enjoy, I think.

00:46:43.175 --> 00:46:45.016
Having something like speed up the process.

00:46:45.735 --> 00:46:47.416
But there's this whole other group of people

00:46:47.416 --> 00:46:49.495
who probably do, I guess,

00:46:49.495 --> 00:46:51.495
want to snap things into existence.

00:46:53.495 --> 00:46:53.735
Yeah.

00:46:53.735 --> 00:46:55.016
But even something like that,

00:46:55.016 --> 00:46:58.456
I mean, you built the thing, you can tell us.

00:46:58.456 --> 00:47:01.976
But even if you could snap your fingers

00:47:01.976 --> 00:47:04.935
and have the problem that that tool solves solved,

00:47:05.495 --> 00:47:07.656
I'm not sure that gives you the same satisfaction either.

00:47:08.143 --> 00:47:10.783
Like, there is something about building a thing and using the thing, and like —

00:47:10.783 --> 00:47:11.903
And it's like, it's my thing.

00:47:11.903 --> 00:47:15.023
Yeah, it's like, look at it work, and I see the spinning wheels,

00:47:15.023 --> 00:47:16.863
and I see it come back with stuff, and I — it's like,

00:47:16.863 --> 00:47:19.343
there is an enjoyment in using it at all.

00:47:19.903 --> 00:47:23.183
And I think that, like, we're not — it's not all just, like,

00:47:23.183 --> 00:47:27.743
how do I maximize some utility of this thing does my particular job.

00:47:27.743 --> 00:47:30.862
Some of it, maybe, it's like, okay, you have a button that fills out your tax forms.

00:47:30.862 --> 00:47:32.063
Okay, that may be a different thing.

00:47:32.063 --> 00:47:32.782
Joy achieved.

00:47:32.782 --> 00:47:34.622
There's a very different, to me, set of things.

00:47:34.622 --> 00:47:37.183
It's like, I just do not want to ever see this again,

00:47:37.183 --> 00:47:41.503
versus I built this partly because it's, like, a thing I like to use.

00:47:41.503 --> 00:47:42.942
A lot of people, like, do woodworking.

00:47:42.942 --> 00:47:45.183
They're not like, snap my fingers and have the thing exist.

00:47:45.183 --> 00:47:46.863
It's like, I want to do the thing.

00:47:46.863 --> 00:47:47.262
Yeah.

00:47:47.262 --> 00:47:48.543
And I think there's still some of that here.

00:47:48.543 --> 00:47:51.183
Yeah, I mean, yeah, I think, like, the — you know, just, yeah,

00:47:51.183 --> 00:47:53.023
for people listening, like, what are they talking about?

00:47:53.023 --> 00:47:56.303
Like, the thing I started building — still started building recently

00:47:56.303 --> 00:48:00.143
as part of some of the, like, agentic development side projects.

00:48:00.143 --> 00:48:01.343
Like, I found myself —

00:48:01.343 --> 00:48:03.742
And just — I think people might have seen, too,

00:48:03.742 --> 00:48:07.343
because we've talked about it on a couple episodes.

00:48:07.343 --> 00:48:12.703
Like, so I think some people might be familiar, but maybe, like, a quick —

00:48:12.703 --> 00:48:15.743
Well, yeah, we'll — I can't even remember.

00:48:15.743 --> 00:48:19.103
I mean, the software is so new, like, it's hard to even know.

00:48:19.103 --> 00:48:22.942
But, you know, I essentially, like many people, I started running —

00:48:22.942 --> 00:48:24.942
I started running multiple Cloud Code sessions,

00:48:24.942 --> 00:48:29.743
and then I found that most of the work that Cloud Code was doing was full of bugs.

00:48:29.743 --> 00:48:32.542
And so I started running separate, additional,

00:48:32.542 --> 00:48:35.983
either Cloud Code or Codex from OpenAI sessions,

00:48:35.983 --> 00:48:40.622
whose entire purpose was to review the work of the other Cloud Code sessions.

00:48:40.622 --> 00:48:44.542
And so I would have three Cloud Code sessions and then three reviewers,

00:48:44.542 --> 00:48:48.542
and all they were doing was review this commit, review this commit, review this commit.

00:48:48.542 --> 00:48:53.023
And so, like, Cloud Code would return control to me, would commit its work,

00:48:53.023 --> 00:48:54.542
and then I would say, here's the commit hash,

00:48:54.542 --> 00:48:56.862
and I would give that to the reviewer, the reviewer session.

00:48:57.423 --> 00:49:00.383
And then, you know, this went on for a period of time,

00:49:00.383 --> 00:49:05.343
and I was like, I'm losing time because I have to manually, like,

00:49:05.343 --> 00:49:07.423
take the commit hash and, like, give it to the reviewer,

00:49:07.423 --> 00:49:08.862
and that's time that's wasted.

00:49:09.902 --> 00:49:11.822
Basically, the whole thing just didn't seem very efficient.

00:49:11.822 --> 00:49:17.343
And so I said to myself, well, you know, this whole process can be automated.

00:49:17.343 --> 00:49:21.983
And so, yeah, so the project RoboRev that we mentioned is basically like,

00:49:21.983 --> 00:49:25.343
you know, it automatically triggers a code review

00:49:25.343 --> 00:49:27.983
whenever the agents return control to you,

00:49:27.983 --> 00:49:32.863
like, whenever they commit and return, get commit and return control.

00:49:32.863 --> 00:49:34.542
And I found that to be really liberating.

00:49:34.542 --> 00:49:38.703
Like, I didn't have to run those extra, you know, codecs or Cloud Code sessions anymore.

00:49:39.662 --> 00:49:43.423
And if I have parallel, like, multiple Cloud Code sessions,

00:49:43.423 --> 00:49:46.943
whenever I return to the session from another side project

00:49:46.943 --> 00:49:51.022
or, you know, another, you know, get work tree or whatever in the same project,

00:49:51.022 --> 00:49:53.343
I have not only the agent has finished what it was doing,

00:49:53.343 --> 00:49:58.063
but then also the associated code review that was done asynchronously

00:49:58.063 --> 00:50:00.063
while I was working on something else.

00:50:00.063 --> 00:50:02.303
And so if I, you know, forget what I was doing,

00:50:02.303 --> 00:50:04.622
or if I'm not sure what to do next, like, it's just easy to say,

00:50:04.622 --> 00:50:09.902
hey, you know, Cloud fix these bugs that were discovered in the work that you just did.

00:50:10.783 --> 00:50:11.503
But you're right.

00:50:11.503 --> 00:50:15.742
Like, I think part of the fun of it was, you know, making a tool,

00:50:15.742 --> 00:50:19.262
seeing, you know, building the tool yourself, seeing the tool work.

00:50:19.343 --> 00:50:26.303
And I think, you know, maybe a side, you know, corollary of that now is that

00:50:26.303 --> 00:50:30.462
a lot of people are going to prefer to use tools of their own making.

00:50:30.462 --> 00:50:34.622
And I find that whenever I show new AI tools,

00:50:34.622 --> 00:50:36.462
or like new tools that I've created to other people,

00:50:37.022 --> 00:50:38.382
usually the response is something like,

00:50:38.382 --> 00:50:41.902
I'm exhausted with how many tools I'm being shown

00:50:41.902 --> 00:50:45.022
and like how many new tools I'm seeing on the internet.

00:50:45.022 --> 00:50:48.303
And like, I have no, you know, the only tool I can manage right now

00:50:48.303 --> 00:50:52.703
is like a single agent session, or maybe like a couple of agent sessions.

00:50:52.703 --> 00:50:56.223
And any other tools beyond that is just, is almost exhausting.

00:50:56.863 --> 00:51:02.223
And I've also felt like that exhaustion of like the head spinning feeling of like

00:51:02.223 --> 00:51:06.223
10 new AI tools and systems and solutions coming out seemingly,

00:51:06.223 --> 00:51:08.223
you know, seemingly every day that, you know,

00:51:08.223 --> 00:51:11.662
influencers are really excited about on social media and on LinkedIn

00:51:11.662 --> 00:51:14.063
and on YouTube videos and things like that.

00:51:14.063 --> 00:51:16.303
And so, you know, for the longest time, like I was,

00:51:16.303 --> 00:51:20.462
I was tuning out a lot of what was going on in LLM world.

00:51:21.343 --> 00:51:24.382
And the only thing that really pulled me in were these CLI coding agents.

00:51:24.382 --> 00:51:28.463
I think prior to that, I was like, you know, not, not impressed, to be honest.

00:51:29.183 --> 00:51:32.222
Yeah. But I think that's like the, that sort of reaction,

00:51:32.222 --> 00:51:35.342
being shown 10 new tools and you have things like that.

00:51:35.342 --> 00:51:37.583
We've all sort of played around with this stuff is,

00:51:38.143 --> 00:51:40.143
that to me is like the content thing where it'd be like,

00:51:40.942 --> 00:51:44.623
if iPhones and like iPhone video editing had just come out,

00:51:44.623 --> 00:51:46.062
it's like, look at my video.

00:51:46.062 --> 00:51:48.542
And it'd be like, oh my God, this, yes, it's very good.

00:51:48.542 --> 00:51:50.782
It's as good as any video I've seen 10 years ago.

00:51:50.782 --> 00:51:52.382
But like, I can't look at this much video.

00:51:52.382 --> 00:51:53.743
Like I'm, I got to tune it out.

00:51:53.743 --> 00:51:54.542
And I think that, I don't know,

00:51:54.542 --> 00:51:57.183
there's this kind of feverish pace to the whole thing

00:51:57.822 --> 00:52:00.782
where all these people make things that seem really good,

00:52:00.782 --> 00:52:03.262
but it's like, I can't, I can't keep up.

00:52:03.262 --> 00:52:08.303
Yeah, Ben, I know we've, we've been down the AI rabbit hole for quite a while.

00:52:08.303 --> 00:52:11.983
One, okay, maybe one thing I'm very curious about is

00:52:12.623 --> 00:52:14.463
when I, before doing this,

00:52:14.463 --> 00:52:16.782
when I asked you what you were most excited about,

00:52:16.782 --> 00:52:18.463
you said joining a boy band.

00:52:19.102 --> 00:52:22.703
And I wonder if you could maybe tell us more about that,

00:52:22.703 --> 00:52:23.662
your boy band dreams.

00:52:24.863 --> 00:52:26.863
I mean, that does seem like a fun gig.

00:52:28.062 --> 00:52:29.342
Okay, basically.

00:52:29.342 --> 00:52:30.382
Yeah, no, sorry, please.

00:52:32.782 --> 00:52:34.382
It's like a model of collaboration.

00:52:35.822 --> 00:52:36.623
So, okay, so you like-

00:52:36.623 --> 00:52:38.062
It's your gas town, isn't it?

00:52:38.942 --> 00:52:42.382
I, you know, gas town's probably not a bad boy band name,

00:52:42.382 --> 00:52:43.262
to be entirely honest.

00:52:45.102 --> 00:52:50.703
That you can, if you like ever interview an exec and being like,

00:52:50.703 --> 00:52:51.983
especially an exec from Salesforce,

00:52:51.983 --> 00:52:53.743
this is apparently famously a thing that Salesforce did.

00:52:55.023 --> 00:52:57.262
You ask them like, what are they good at and stuff like that?

00:52:57.822 --> 00:52:59.502
They would say stuff like, they're just,

00:52:59.502 --> 00:53:02.542
they're incredibly collaborative, just the most collaborative.

00:53:02.542 --> 00:53:05.262
And it's just like, I'm just so good at working with people, great.

00:53:05.262 --> 00:53:06.703
And I feel like one of the things we all say like,

00:53:06.703 --> 00:53:07.822
oh, I'm pretty, I'm collaborative.

00:53:07.822 --> 00:53:08.942
I'm like, you know, whatever.

00:53:08.942 --> 00:53:11.983
I'm like not, I don't really want to work with that many people.

00:53:11.983 --> 00:53:13.822
Like, I don't want to, it's like a lot.

00:53:15.262 --> 00:53:19.423
And you want to work with some people, but like not an army of people.

00:53:19.423 --> 00:53:21.903
I don't want to work with the whole gas town army.

00:53:22.542 --> 00:53:25.822
And I think it's more fun to work with like a small group of people

00:53:25.822 --> 00:53:28.703
who's like all committed to a project and like wants to do the thing.

00:53:28.703 --> 00:53:33.262
And it's basically a model of collaboration, like a boy band,

00:53:33.262 --> 00:53:35.262
where it's like, there's a handful of us.

00:53:35.262 --> 00:53:36.863
We all have our fun little personalities.

00:53:36.863 --> 00:53:37.983
We do our own things.

00:53:37.983 --> 00:53:39.423
You could do your own thing if you wanted to,

00:53:39.423 --> 00:53:41.183
but you kind of like being a part of this thing.

00:53:41.183 --> 00:53:43.102
Maybe sometimes you kind of do a little bit of your own thing,

00:53:43.102 --> 00:53:46.782
but like ultimately we all have to have to do the same song and dance.

00:53:48.143 --> 00:53:50.942
But you can maintain some amount of like independence in what you are.

00:53:50.942 --> 00:53:57.102
And it's not like each person in the boy band is overseeing enormous departments.

00:53:57.102 --> 00:53:59.502
Their job isn't managing a ton of people.

00:53:59.502 --> 00:54:01.423
The job is like, no, I make the thing.

00:54:02.222 --> 00:54:09.822
Um, historically to me, there's always been like one of the downsides of startups

00:54:09.822 --> 00:54:12.623
is in some ways you get punished if you're successful

00:54:12.623 --> 00:54:14.463
because you have to go hire a bunch of people.

00:54:14.463 --> 00:54:18.623
And like you become the, oh, I have to manage tons of people

00:54:18.623 --> 00:54:20.062
and the things that go along with that.

00:54:20.062 --> 00:54:22.062
And sometimes there's things about that that are fun and you like,

00:54:22.062 --> 00:54:25.502
