01:08:27.926 --> 01:08:33.047
it keeps you really attached. And I started giving talk — like, I really like that style for talks,

01:08:33.047 --> 01:08:36.406
and so that's, like, kind of the style I gave for talks. And the thing that creates is, like,

01:08:37.846 --> 01:08:42.247
there's a certain pace to it that I, like — it requires you to kind of weave a bunch of stuff

01:08:42.247 --> 01:08:47.846
into it, because you can't just be, like, AI, picture of AI. You can't — computer picture.

01:08:47.846 --> 01:08:52.887
You have to come up with, like, little vignettes that follow along throughout the course of it.

01:08:54.167 --> 01:08:58.646
I think this is much more entertaining. And so, like, a lot of the blog style actually was more

01:08:58.646 --> 01:09:02.807
of, like, how does that look on paper? I'm not sure it delivers on that, but, like, that's where

01:09:04.006 --> 01:09:08.486
there's, like, footnotes and stuff that are sort of, like, the whole thing is a little bit of,

01:09:08.486 --> 01:09:11.047
like, there's a sub-narrative to it that's, like, me entertaining myself.

01:09:12.727 --> 01:09:14.807
Because, again, it's about sequel, and, like, my God.

01:09:14.807 --> 01:09:18.247
Yeah, I mean, it is interesting. It's, like, all the elements of, like,

01:09:19.366 --> 01:09:25.366
a lot of, like, stream of thought and collage and association, but it is crazy that it all, like,

01:09:26.167 --> 01:09:31.206
comes back to data. I feel like it's, like, really — not to butter you up too hard,

01:09:31.206 --> 01:09:32.406
but it's interesting to read.

01:09:32.406 --> 01:09:35.447
It, to some degree, comes back. Like, I'm not going to — you know,

01:09:35.447 --> 01:09:37.206
sometimes they don't really tie together.

01:09:37.206 --> 01:09:40.247
Are you saying there's no promises? You might, like, at some point,

01:09:40.247 --> 01:09:41.687
drift off data and go full?

01:09:42.807 --> 01:09:46.727
Well, yeah. Like, broadly, yeah. And I would say I, like, at this point,

01:09:46.727 --> 01:09:51.846
mostly have. Like, there are still things there, but, like, I don't — it's not a lot about

01:09:52.486 --> 01:09:54.087
ETL tools these days.

01:09:54.087 --> 01:09:54.566
Yeah.

01:09:54.566 --> 01:09:55.126
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:09:56.566 --> 01:10:01.687
I mean, on the subject of, like, you know, like, small — like, small teams and small companies,

01:10:01.687 --> 01:10:07.047
like, I feel like examples of companies that have remained small and yet been really successful,

01:10:07.047 --> 01:10:08.486
like, there just aren't that many.

01:10:08.486 --> 01:10:13.126
I think, like, Craigslist is always the canonical example of a company that, you know,

01:10:13.126 --> 01:10:19.047
still has the same, you know, very bland, you know, utilitarian website that it had,

01:10:19.047 --> 01:10:20.406
you know, 20 or 30 years ago.

01:10:20.406 --> 01:10:22.327
I don't know when it started. No, over 20 years ago.

01:10:23.207 --> 01:10:27.207
And yet they have tons of revenue and, like, some really — some really small team.

01:10:27.767 --> 01:10:32.887
And, you know, me as a software developer, like, I always found myself torn between,

01:10:32.887 --> 01:10:37.447
like, the desire to, like, build open-source software and, like, make the world a better

01:10:37.447 --> 01:10:41.207
place through, like, building tools and giving them away for free on the internet,

01:10:41.207 --> 01:10:45.207
with the downside that it's hard to do that in a sustainable way, like, to get people — very

01:10:45.207 --> 01:10:49.607
hard to get people to pay you to do that for a long period of time. It's hard to be able to hire

01:10:49.607 --> 01:10:54.086
people because people need salaries and they need health insurance and all those things.

01:10:54.086 --> 01:10:57.927
And on the other end, you know, the other — you know, and you have entrepreneurship and

01:10:58.806 --> 01:11:03.207
starting, you know, starting companies and then invariably, you know, with the way the world works,

01:11:03.207 --> 01:11:07.126
like, you get nudged into the, like, you know, the venture capital and the raising money.

01:11:07.126 --> 01:11:10.406
And that has a lot of strings attached. There's a lot of expectations that,

01:11:10.406 --> 01:11:13.846
you know, everyone has in terms of, like, how fast you're going to grow and how many people

01:11:13.846 --> 01:11:18.647
you're going to hire. And then, you know, that gets really complicated, as you know.

01:11:19.607 --> 01:11:24.647
And so I think one optimistic, you know, hope that I have is that, you know,

01:11:24.647 --> 01:11:30.167
there might be some, like, new model of, you know, people that build software in the world

01:11:30.167 --> 01:11:33.846
and can do — you know, build new things or, like, create things that have impact

01:11:33.846 --> 01:11:38.727
that's like neither of those things and yet, like, can be fun and sustainable,

01:11:38.727 --> 01:11:41.526
like, kind of the best of both worlds. And I don't know what that looks like,

01:11:41.526 --> 01:11:46.806
but something I'm really interested in. I mean, like, my answer to that is it's a —

01:11:46.806 --> 01:11:53.367
it looks like a business. It's a small business. Like, it's only in software where — and this

01:11:53.367 --> 01:11:56.487
made sense, again, kind of the economics of, like, building software. There's a ton of upfront

01:11:56.487 --> 01:12:01.447
cost and stuff. But only in software, like, we're going to start a thing that's going to be 10

01:12:01.447 --> 01:12:06.246
people and we're going to try to make more money than we spent. That's the goal. And, like, you

01:12:06.246 --> 01:12:11.447
start a restaurant, duh. Like, yes, that's the goal. But in software, it's like, that's a

01:12:11.447 --> 01:12:14.246
ridiculous goal. Like, how are you going to grow? How are you going to —

01:12:14.246 --> 01:12:18.566
It's kind of famously parodied in Silicon Valley. It's like revenue. No, no, you want to be pre-revenue.

01:12:18.566 --> 01:12:22.566
Yeah, exactly. It's like, there's very much a model for, like, a handful of people working

01:12:22.566 --> 01:12:25.927
on a fun thing forever that you can be sustainable. It's like, that's a business.

01:12:26.966 --> 01:12:32.327
But start — again, I think it is — it's not just, like, the VC ecosystem. It's like,

01:12:32.327 --> 01:12:35.607
the economics of software have not been able to support that. You do have to

01:12:35.607 --> 01:12:41.286
spend $5 million before you can sell anything. You're in a lot of debt. And, like, that doesn't

01:12:41.286 --> 01:12:45.767
quite work. And so — but now you don't have to be. Like, you can get to the point where you can

01:12:45.767 --> 01:12:51.047
probably make — you can be probably making money after a year of one person working on a thing.

01:12:51.686 --> 01:12:55.607
And, like, all right, that's — yeah, that's just a business. And I don't know, it seems like

01:12:55.607 --> 01:12:59.927
if building stuff is fun and a business you can run forever isn't bad, then, like,

01:13:00.566 --> 01:13:03.767
not a bad gig. Maybe. No, I don't know. Maybe it doesn't work, and maybe software is too, like,

01:13:04.406 --> 01:13:08.647
winner-take-all, and so you have to get super huge. But I don't know. I'm, like, not that cynical

01:13:08.647 --> 01:13:13.207
about that, I think. I think it's like, how many people do you really need to really love a thing

01:13:13.207 --> 01:13:16.246
to make it sustainable for a handful of people? Not that many. Yeah, it does seem like there's a

01:13:16.246 --> 01:13:23.686
big space for, like, a small useful thing that, like, people are willing to pay monthly for or

01:13:23.686 --> 01:13:29.846
something. Yeah, and it does — this isn't quite right, because there's certainly a lot of things

01:13:29.846 --> 01:13:36.327
that are just, like, pure productivity tools, but it starts to feel a little bit more art-oriented

01:13:36.327 --> 01:13:40.406
or, like, content-oriented. It's almost like Substack, but, like, Substack for, you know,

01:13:40.406 --> 01:13:45.047
somebody's, like, vibe-coded software. Yeah, like, there was — one of the things I've noticed is

01:13:45.047 --> 01:13:50.727
people seem to have replaced — in a lot of ways, decks have gotten replaced with, like,

01:13:51.367 --> 01:13:54.727
Vercell apps, because you can kind of do it in the same amount of time. You're like,

01:13:54.727 --> 01:13:58.887
oh, you want to give a demo of something? I just made a thing. Like, you get random pitches from

01:13:58.887 --> 01:14:02.327
people about, like, check out this thing or whatever. I have gotten a lot of those that

01:14:02.327 --> 01:14:07.526
are links to Vercell apps now, because it's about — it used to be, like, here's a PDF of some slides

01:14:07.526 --> 01:14:11.447
or whatever, and now it's like, why would I do that? I can make a little clicky app thing. And

01:14:11.447 --> 01:14:16.246
so, I don't know, that feels more like it's just — software is just content at that point,

01:14:16.246 --> 01:14:20.887
as opposed to, like, a tool for anything. It's just like, I just have a much more flexible canvas

01:14:20.887 --> 01:14:24.647
to make a thing I want to make. It's interesting that you have a deck being replaced with a

01:14:24.647 --> 01:14:30.487
Vercell app, which is like, like, deck plus plus, just a little bit more, like,

01:14:30.487 --> 01:14:37.687
interactivity, that the bar is just way lower. Yeah, and it's not that different than — what's

01:14:37.687 --> 01:14:40.727
the simplest version for me to explain something? It's a bunch of text. Okay, what's the slightly

01:14:40.727 --> 01:14:45.127
more complicated version? A Word doc with text, with, like, some bullets and some nice formatting.

01:14:45.127 --> 01:14:49.047
What's, like, a very flexible version? Like, a deck, because it's just a — it's a bunch of

01:14:49.047 --> 01:14:52.406
static canvases that I can literally draw anything I want on. What's an even more complicated

01:14:52.406 --> 01:14:58.406
version? A deck that I can click on. That's kind of a website? Like, okay, it's not that different.

01:14:58.406 --> 01:15:04.646
Yeah, and are you looking at decks? Like, what's your — what's bringing decks past your eyes?

01:15:05.286 --> 01:15:10.167
I mean, so people periodically reach out because of the blog stuff. You'll complain about something,

01:15:10.167 --> 01:15:13.766
and I'll be like, well, actually, here's my version. They're like, would love your take on —

01:15:13.766 --> 01:15:19.446
Yeah. Which, I mean, as a slight aside, one thing that does sort of — is a bit of a character of

01:15:19.446 --> 01:15:22.567
that is because I complain about a lot of stuff, people mostly will send things and be like,

01:15:23.030 --> 01:15:25.190
Give me your worst opinion on this.

01:15:25.830 --> 01:15:29.270
And so it's kind of asking for a lot of like, what do you hate about it?

01:15:30.870 --> 01:15:31.830
Which some things are very good.

01:15:31.830 --> 01:15:33.590
Yeah, how do you like, how's that job?

01:15:34.807 --> 01:15:37.687
Do you like doing the job of, uh, you hate this?

01:15:37.687 --> 01:15:38.967
Like, what do you hate about this?

01:15:38.967 --> 01:15:39.927
Job is a real stretch.

01:15:39.927 --> 01:15:40.427
Yeah.

01:15:41.847 --> 01:15:46.247
I don't, I mean, I don't, I'm not, like, I hate everything that you do.

01:15:48.247 --> 01:15:56.167
That said, I do think there is a relatively useful hole in, like, VCs in that, where

01:15:56.887 --> 01:16:02.407
if you go pitch Sequoia and they don't like it, they will tell you, like,

01:16:03.366 --> 01:16:04.167
it's too early.

01:16:04.167 --> 01:16:05.526
Nobody was pounding on the table.

01:16:05.526 --> 01:16:06.247
We really like it.

01:16:06.247 --> 01:16:07.607
We'd love to see it next round.

01:16:07.607 --> 01:16:08.647
Like, we're just not there.

01:16:08.647 --> 01:16:10.407
We just couldn't, we just couldn't quite get there.

01:16:10.407 --> 01:16:11.447
Market wasn't quite big enough.

01:16:11.447 --> 01:16:13.366
We had questions about competitors.

01:16:13.366 --> 01:16:14.567
Like, they will tell you nothing.

01:16:15.366 --> 01:16:17.447
And the reason they tell you nothing is because they have no incentive to tell you anything

01:16:17.447 --> 01:16:17.767
other than that.

01:16:17.767 --> 01:16:21.287
Like, why would they tell you something that's gonna, why would they tell you what they really

01:16:21.287 --> 01:16:25.206
think, which is probably, like, I hated the way that founder dressed.

01:16:25.206 --> 01:16:30.486
Like, they reject you, one, I mean, Sequoia, not just Sequoia, like every VC, you get rejected

01:16:30.486 --> 01:16:31.767
probably for emotional reasons.

01:16:31.767 --> 01:16:35.047
You get probably rejected because, like, literally two minutes into the pitch, they don't take

01:16:35.047 --> 01:16:38.087
you seriously and they're tuned out and they're off looking at something else.

01:16:39.687 --> 01:16:42.887
Maybe they reject you for, like, real material reasons and, like, they really evaluated it

01:16:42.887 --> 01:16:43.367
and didn't like it.

01:16:43.367 --> 01:16:46.166
But, like, they're not gonna give you that memo of the thing they said.

01:16:46.166 --> 01:16:48.647
And it's, like, they want you to like them so you come back next time.

01:16:48.647 --> 01:16:51.287
If you do are successful, they want to, like, maintain optionality of that deal.

01:16:52.007 --> 01:16:55.526
And it's very frustrating when you're pitching because you just don't get anything honest.

01:16:55.526 --> 01:16:59.846
You get a lot of, like, kind of soft, ah, it's just not for us yet.

01:16:59.846 --> 01:17:02.647
We'd like to see a little bit more, a little more meat on the bone.

01:17:02.647 --> 01:17:03.446
And you're, like, okay.

01:17:05.206 --> 01:17:08.806
But I think, so I think, like, there is a little bit of a, this is a, like, I am not

01:17:08.806 --> 01:17:12.007
a VC, nor do I give feedback that people should listen to.

01:17:12.007 --> 01:17:16.007
But I would appreciate a VC where you walk into it and it's a little bit of, like, the

01:17:16.007 --> 01:17:20.086
Simon Cowell of VCs where you're, like, they're gonna hate it.

01:17:20.086 --> 01:17:22.727
I'm not gonna be offended when they hate it because I know they hate it.

01:17:22.727 --> 01:17:25.446
And if they like it, Simon Cowell liked my song.

01:17:25.446 --> 01:17:26.086
Like, oh my God.

01:17:26.727 --> 01:17:31.846
I would pitch that VC because I, like, the worst that happens is the thing I expect to

01:17:31.846 --> 01:17:32.086
happen.

01:17:33.206 --> 01:17:33.927
And there's a million others.

01:17:33.927 --> 01:17:35.367
I'll just go pitch them for the actual money.

01:17:35.367 --> 01:17:36.486
And so, like, I don't know.

01:17:39.126 --> 01:17:41.927
The VCs have, like, sort of weird, those are, like, value systems like this.

01:17:41.927 --> 01:17:43.367
But, like, there's some weird incentives there.

01:17:43.367 --> 01:17:49.927
And so I do think, like, yeah, what you really think is nice to hear in an uncomfortable

01:17:49.927 --> 01:17:50.567
way sometimes.

01:17:50.567 --> 01:17:55.447
But again, if Simon Cowell tells you you're bad, you're not gonna be, like, I must suck.

01:17:55.447 --> 01:17:57.846
You're gonna be, like, that's his job.

01:17:57.846 --> 01:17:58.567
That's what he does.

01:17:58.567 --> 01:17:59.206
That's his shtick.

01:17:59.766 --> 01:18:00.486
Yeah.

01:18:00.486 --> 01:18:01.206
Yeah, that's fair.

01:18:02.326 --> 01:18:02.567
I don't know.

01:18:02.567 --> 01:18:03.686
You've pitched a lot of VCs.

01:18:03.686 --> 01:18:04.167
Maybe you have.

01:18:04.887 --> 01:18:09.126
No, I largely agree with what you're saying.

01:18:09.126 --> 01:18:16.647
I mean, it's, especially in Silicon Valley, it's rare to hear, like, honest feedback.

01:18:16.647 --> 01:18:21.927
Like, and I've known, you know, I've known VCs and have been in pitches where I've received,

01:18:21.927 --> 01:18:23.287
like, honest feedback.

01:18:23.287 --> 01:18:24.647
Like, this is not good.

01:18:24.647 --> 01:18:25.686
You shouldn't be doing this.

01:18:25.686 --> 01:18:27.046
You should be doing something else.

01:18:27.046 --> 01:18:30.007
Like, the way that you're approaching this problem is wrong.

01:18:30.007 --> 01:18:33.527
And it is refreshing to get those, like, to get those takes.

01:18:33.527 --> 01:18:38.887
But, you know, but usually, like, I think professional, you know, venture investors

01:18:38.887 --> 01:18:42.807
are looking at so many pitches and talking to so many founders that generally, like,

01:18:42.807 --> 01:18:43.927
they're just pattern matching.

01:18:43.927 --> 01:18:48.807
Like, they don't have, you know, the time or energy to, especially at the early stage,

01:18:48.807 --> 01:18:50.406
like, to think super hard about things.

01:18:50.406 --> 01:18:54.966
And so it's basically like, you know, have I seen any, you know, similar companies in

01:18:54.966 --> 01:18:57.287
the past that have done this successfully?

01:18:57.287 --> 01:19:01.126
Like, does this, the way that this product is being sold, like, does that make sense?

01:19:01.126 --> 01:19:03.287
Like, are they selling to the right people?

01:19:03.287 --> 01:19:06.727
Like, does the tech, does the team seem credible?

01:19:07.287 --> 01:19:11.606
Surprisingly often, like, you look at the backgrounds of the, you know, the founders

01:19:11.606 --> 01:19:15.846
of a company and, you know, it's like, they can't build this.

01:19:15.927 --> 01:19:20.326
Like, are they, you know, if there's going to be a successful product, it shouldn't be,

01:19:20.326 --> 01:19:21.287
it shouldn't be this team.

01:19:21.287 --> 01:19:24.647
And that's often, you know, in many cases, that's just the right answer.

01:19:24.647 --> 01:19:29.846
And it isn't always the most, unfortunately, very frustratingly, it's not the most competent

01:19:29.846 --> 01:19:33.206
and qualified founders that, you know, succeed in the space.

01:19:33.206 --> 01:19:37.367
And I know that, you know, often, you know, it's the founders who were like, had the right

01:19:37.367 --> 01:19:40.727
background, were at the right place at the right time, and yet still, you know, came

01:19:40.727 --> 01:19:44.727
in second or came in, you know, fifth, who ended up, you know, very frustrated and bitter.

01:19:45.686 --> 01:19:49.206
But so that's just kind of how the cookie crumbles, unfortunately.

01:19:50.167 --> 01:19:56.086
But yeah, it's a lot of, you know, it's a lot of pattern matching, because ultimately,

01:19:56.086 --> 01:20:01.126
yeah, like, in investing, you want to maintain relationships, not burn bridges.

01:20:01.126 --> 01:20:04.966
You don't want somebody to come away from interaction being offended or being like,

01:20:04.966 --> 01:20:06.406
you know, that guy was a jerk.

01:20:06.406 --> 01:20:08.646
You know, he was honest, but he was a jerk, you know?

01:20:09.526 --> 01:20:10.487
And you should never be a jerk.

01:20:10.487 --> 01:20:11.366
Like, I'm never a jerk.

01:20:11.366 --> 01:20:11.926
So yeah.

01:20:11.926 --> 01:20:16.806
And to me, like, yeah, I think a lot of times VCs aren't, don't give totally truthful feedback,

01:20:16.806 --> 01:20:18.086
because they're trying to be nice.

01:20:18.086 --> 01:20:21.447
And a lot of times the answer is like, you're not the horse I want to bet on.

01:20:21.447 --> 01:20:25.366
And like, I don't know, what use is telling somebody that, you know, like, so yeah.

01:20:26.246 --> 01:20:32.167
But as a result of that, I think you also just get like, kind of very sort of soft answers.

01:20:33.526 --> 01:20:36.806
It's nice, though, that you're, well, I don't know if you want more of these,

01:20:36.806 --> 01:20:43.526
but that you're giving people kind of, no, I don't want to say radical candor.

01:20:43.526 --> 01:20:46.246
You're giving people like, candid feedback, right?

01:20:46.806 --> 01:20:50.167
Yeah, I mean, I'm certainly not trying to like, maintain some sort of set of deal flow

01:20:50.167 --> 01:20:51.047
around that sort of stuff.

01:20:52.086 --> 01:20:53.767
But also, I don't know, that's like, kind of what I would want.

01:20:53.767 --> 01:20:55.686
And if you're nice about it, it's fine.

01:20:56.246 --> 01:20:57.767
And maybe, I mean, I don't know, I try to be.

01:20:58.406 --> 01:20:59.767
Yeah, yeah.

01:20:59.767 --> 01:21:00.246
Yeah, I don't know.

01:21:00.246 --> 01:21:02.167
And I was like, I don't know, for me, that's like, that stuff's interesting.

01:21:02.167 --> 01:21:04.007
It's interesting to see what other people are working on and stuff, so.

01:21:04.007 --> 01:21:04.507
Yeah.

01:21:05.287 --> 01:21:07.926
Anything you're excited for this year?

01:21:07.926 --> 01:21:11.366
Or what are you most excited for this year, would you say?

01:21:11.366 --> 01:21:13.846
I mean, it's, I don't know, there's a bunch of stuff.

01:21:14.727 --> 01:21:17.686
The way all this stuff changes things is like, exciting and a very,

01:21:18.966 --> 01:21:22.406
I don't know, do I, maybe we could just have like, a down year.

01:21:23.207 --> 01:21:25.846
Maybe we could just, just stop for a bit.

01:21:25.846 --> 01:21:26.327
Right.

01:21:26.327 --> 01:21:26.827
Like.

01:21:27.366 --> 01:21:29.126
It's like, all gas, no brakes.

01:21:29.126 --> 01:21:30.567
We need like, a moment to catch up.

01:21:31.126 --> 01:21:33.287
Can we just all, so I don't know.

01:21:33.526 --> 01:21:36.646
Like, I am sure there are things that will come out that will be,

01:21:37.366 --> 01:21:38.727
you like and are fun and stuff like that.

01:21:38.727 --> 01:21:42.806
And I think, I think Cloud Code is a good example to me of what that has been,

